addr="dummit-2004-abstract"
title="Abstract Algebra">Abstract Algebra</fr:link> Section 4.1</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> be a set, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link
type="local"
href="gr-000G.xml"
addr="gr-000G"
title="Group">Group</fr:link>. A <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Permutation Representation</html:dfn> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is a group morphism <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\rho \colon  G\to \mathop {\textrm {Sym}}\nolimits (X)]]></fr:tex> from <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> to the <fr:link
type="local"
href="gr-000F.xml"
addr="gr-000F"
title="Symmetric group of a set">symmetric group of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex></fr:link>.</fr:p><fr:p>When <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g\in  G]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  X]]></fr:tex>, we write <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g\cdot  x]]></fr:tex> instead of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\rho (g)(x)]]></fr:tex>. If there's ambiguity, we'll write <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\rho _{g}(x)]]></fr:tex> to stress which representation we're using.</fr:p><fr:p>More generally, a <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Permutation Representation</html:dfn> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> (without any mention of the representation space <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>) consists of a set <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> equipped with a group morphism <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\rho \colon  G\to \mathop {\textrm {Sym}}\nolimits (X)]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
 
   
